text.tspan: Potential and pitfalls of eukaryotic metagenome skimming:

flowRoot.flowPara: Metagenomic sequencing with only a single library layout is used to quickly and cheaply assess the taxonomic and functional complexity of large and diverse microbial communities. On the example of lichens we investigate to what extent such metagenome skimming approaches are applicable for the in-depth characterizations of genomes represented in obligate symbiotic communities of eukaryotes. Specifically we ask how a eukaryotic species mixture with larger and more repeat-rich genomes influences different de novo assembly paradigms, realised in de Brujin Graph based methods or Overlap Layout based assemblers and how to optimize assembly parameters as k-mer or overlap sizes.

To address these questions, we performed an in silico study, simulating twin sets for a lichen genome skimming experiment. We show that the quality of genome reconstructions from such data depends on assembler choice, but more importantly also on the ratio of the taxa in the metagenome and the parameter optimisation strategy. In particular, optimising for assembly metrics such as N50 can in extreme cases lead to the exclusion of complete genomes from the assembly. Transfering the results of the simulations to a real-world metagenome skimming experiment of the lichen Lasallia pustulata, we not only see a larger species diversity, but also hints to biased sequencing coverage for the algal genome.

Twin sets are valuable for guiding strategic decisions during planning of metagenome sequencing and assembly.
Assembler performance already varies substantially for single species data.
Mixing data from different species inflates the assembler performance differences, with MIRA & SPAdes yielding the most contiguous sequences throughout all twin sets.
Optimising the assembly parameters using the N50 size as quality measure can lead to the preclusion of entire species represented in a metagenome.

Despite a 10x coverage, the algal genome assembly is highly fragmented, representing <1/4 of the estimated genome size. This hints towards an uneven algal genome coverage, as a result of a biased library preparation.

Single species data Almost all assemblers reconstruct the two genomes over their full length from the simulated sequences (Fig. 3, column 0:10 & 10:0), however with varying contiguity. For the alga most assemblers exceeded the NG50 size of the original draft assembly. For the fungus, it appears that the repetitive nature of the genome (c.f. Fig. 2) hinders the generation of longer contigs with the present WGS library layout (Fig. 4).

Mixed species data Completeness of the genome reconstructions depends heavily on assembler choice and coverage ratios. MIRA and SPAdes perform best across all data sets. In contrast Velvet and the metagenome assemblers fail to assemble large parts of the low coverage genome once coverage ratios become extreme (Fig. 3, 1:9 - 3:7, 9:1).

Parameter optimization for N50 impairs metagenome assembly Contigs from the low coverage genomes tend to be short, decreasing the overall N50 size. Increasing the word length k to larger values shifts the word frequencies of the low coverage genomes to overlap with those introduced by sequencing errors (Fig. 6). Consequently, they are ignored during assembly resulting in a larger N50 size.

L. pustulata The WGS data was assembled with MIRA and contigs were taxonomically assigned using MEGAN [13]. The algal assembly is much more fragmented than expected given the in silico study (Box III). It appears that this is a result of a biased library preparation, yielding a highly uneven read coverage for the algal genome.

Merge reads simulated from either reference genomes into L. pustulata twin sets with

Figure 1: Workflow for generating twin sets resembling a real sequencing experiment with respect to insert size distribution, read number and read length.

flowRoot.flowPara: DNA from a thallus of Lasallia pustulata was sequenced using Illumina MiSeq technology, yielding 15 million paired-end reads with a length of 250 bp. To estimate the insert size distribution, we joined overlapping read pairs using FLASH [1] and fitted a censored Weibull distribution to the observed insert size distribution (Fig. 1, A).

The scaffolds of the genomes of Cladonia grayi [2] and Asterochloris sp. [3] were each concatenated to create a contiguous pseudo-chromosome, respectively (Fig. 1, B). Both were checked for repeat content [4] (Box 1) & self-similarity [5] (Fig. 2).

Using the pseudo-chromosomes as templates, we simulated reads with ART [6], parameterized with the values estimated from the L. pustulata data. Subsequently, we compiled 11 twin sets by mixing simulated fungal and algal reads at varying ratios (Table 1).
